---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About the Author"
  description="Malcolm Smith is the author of Love Over Exile. This is his personal story of surviving parental alienation — and why he wrote the book."
  ogType="profile"
>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="section about-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="about-hero-inner">
        <div class="about-photo-wrap">
          <img
            src="/images/malcolm-smith-author-love-over-exile.jpg"
            alt="Malcolm Smith — author of Love Over Exile"
            width="460"
            height="540"
            loading="eager"
            decoding="async"
            class="about-photo"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="about-hero-content">
          <p class="eyebrow">About the author</p>
          <h1>Malcolm Smith</h1>
          <p class="about-subtitle">
            Author. Alienated parent. Father.
          </p>
          <blockquote class="pull-quote">
            "I didn't write this book because I had all the answers.
            I wrote it because I needed it to exist — and it didn't."
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Story -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container-narrow prose">

      <h2>The beginning</h2>
      <p>
        Malcolm Smith's experience of parental alienation began like most do — not with a single
        dramatic event, but with a slow erosion. A child who became distant. Phone calls that
        went unanswered. Messages passed through lawyers. A legal system that moved at a pace
        wholly out of step with the damage being done.
      </p>
      <p>
        What followed were years of navigating family courts, therapeutic interventions, and the
        particular kind of grief that comes from losing someone who is still alive — who you
        love more than anything — and who no longer seems to know who you are.
      </p>

      <h2>Why he wrote the book</h2>
      <p>
        When Malcolm looked for resources that spoke to his experience — not clinical literature,
        not legal guides, but something human — he found almost nothing. There were advocacy
        organisations arguing about whether parental alienation was "real." There were support
        forums full of anger and despair. There was very little that offered both practical help
        and a pathway toward something other than bitterness.
      </p>
      <p>
        So he wrote it himself. <em>Love Over Exile</em> is the book he needed — and didn't have.
        It is honest about the legal and systemic failures. It is practical about what actually
        helps. And it is grounded in a core conviction: that love, maintained over years, across
        distance and rejection, is not weakness. It is the only thing that has a chance of
        working — for you, and eventually, for your child.
      </p>

      <h2>The name</h2>
      <p>
        The title comes from a choice that every alienated parent faces: whether to let
        the pain of exile harden into resentment, or to continue choosing love — not as
        a sentimental gesture, but as a deliberate, daily act of refusing to become what
        the situation might make you.
      </p>
      <p>
        Love Over Exile is not about pretending things are fine. It is about choosing, in full
        knowledge of how much it costs, to stay a loving presence in your child's life — even
        when your child cannot see you.
      </p>

      <h2>What Malcolm believes</h2>
      <p>
        Parental alienation is under-researched, under-recognised, and poorly handled by the
        institutions that should protect children from it. The parents who suffer it often do so
        in isolation, without language for what is happening to them, without community, and
        without a roadmap for the long journey ahead.
      </p>
      <p>
        That isolation is what this website, this community, and this book are designed to end.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section class="section section-alt" style="text-align:center;">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <h2>Read the book</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--color-charcoal-mid); margin-bottom:2rem;">
        Join the waitlist for <em>Love Over Exile</em> — and get the free Survival Guide
        while you wait.
      </p>
      <div style="display:flex; gap:1rem; justify-content:center; flex-wrap:wrap;">
        <a href="/the-book" class="btn btn-primary">Join the Waitlist</a>
        <a href="/free-guide" class="btn btn-outline">Get the Free Guide</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
.about-hero { padding-block: 5rem; }
.about-hero-inner {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 460px 1fr;
  gap: 4rem;
  align-items: center;
}
.about-photo {
  width: 100%;
  border-radius: 16px;
  object-fit: cover;
  aspect-ratio: 5/6;
  background: var(--color-border);
}
.eyebrow {
  font-size: 0.78rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  letter-spacing: 0.1em;
  text-transform: uppercase;
  color: var(--color-amber);
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}
.about-subtitle {
  font-family: var(--font-serif);
  font-size: 1.2rem;
  font-style: italic;
  color: var(--color-charcoal-mid);
  margin-bottom: 2rem;
}

@media (max-width: 900px) {
  .about-hero-inner { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .about-photo-wrap { display: none; }
}
</style>
